===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/dʒir/}}
* {{rhymes|ɪə(r)}}

===Etymology 1===
Perhaps a corruption of {{term|lang=en|cheer||to salute with cheers}}, taken in an ironical sense; or more probably from {{etyl|nl}} {{term|lang=nl|gekscheren||to jeer|lit=to shear the fool}}, from {{term|gek||a fool|lang=nl}} (see {{term|geck|lang=en}}) + {{term|scheren||to shear|lang=nl}} (see {{term|shear|lang=en|pos=v}}).

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A railing [[remark]] or reflection; a [[scoff]]; a [[taunt]]; a biting [[jest]]; a [[flout]]; a [[jibe]]; [[mockery]].
#* '''1711''', [[w:Jonathan Swift|Jonathan Swift]], The Fable of Midas, in ''The Works of Jonathan Swift'', D.D., Vol XII, Sir Walter Scott, ed., Edinburgh: Archibald Constable and Co., 1824, pages 302-5,
#*: Midas, exposed to all their '''jeers''', Had lost his art, and kept his ears.

